How to Finance Green Transition
In New York—This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the UN to assess the global war on climate change and submit new carbon reduction commitments.
Climate crisis is a big deal, and we're moving at a pace that's far too slow.
We're lagging behind in shifting into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires cooperation and efforts from both public and private sectors.
Luckily, through the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaborations to mitigate climate change are increasing more and more.
Under the leadership of UN Climate Action Special Envoy Michael Bloomberg, CFLI was established, with the goal of mobilizing global private capital to tackle this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report entitled "Financing the Low Carbon Future", which lists ways to expand green finance to support a orderly low-carbon economic transition, and proposes public-private cooperation opportunities to achieve the 2015 Paris Agreement targets.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the world's largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects.
However, in response to the call of the heads of state of European countries and the newly elected President of the European Commission, von der Leyen, we are now ready to take on even greater ambitions, and strengthen the role of EIB as the EU's dedicated climate bank.
The EIB will implement mainstreaming of climate considerations, directing low-carbon investments, and at least 1 trillion euros will be invested in low-carbon projects over the next ten years.
To achieve this goal, by 2025, at least 50% of EIB financing will be used for climate action and environmental sustainability.
By the end of 2020, we will streamline all our financing activities to be in line with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that depend on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As a European bank, our mission is to invest in the future of Europe, and the most pressing issue is climate change.
The urgency of the climate crisis is a reflection of our determination.
Just this summer, European countries have suffered from record-breaking heatwaves and crop failures, caused by last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-related phenomena cost major cities tens of billions of dollars every year, and threaten even more lives.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, because providing funding for new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that troubles the world's major cities.
Changing the investment model will be able to accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
Market forces increasingly favor clean energy, moving away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, a significant portion of the US coal-fired power plants retired, while the clean energy industry created 3.3 million jobs, and the coal industry had fewer than 100,000 jobs.
Furthermore, an increasing number of American cities and states have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from Beyond Carbon, a plan launched by the Bloomberg Philanthropies last year, aimed at fully decarbonizing the US economy.
As an international community, we not only need to invest in clean energy but also need to reduce investment in dirty energy.
Looking at the subsidies for fossil fuels, we are actually still spending money promoting climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to guide investment towards electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive a green transformation.
These investments will yield huge returns, including the enormous cost imposed on public health by air pollution.
Except for that, we can take numerous measures to guide the necessary funds.
Firstly, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, companies and investors have known nothing about climate-related risks, not knowing the rationality of reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from the impact of extreme weather.
This is starting to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to configure capital in a more sustainable way, and also allowing investors to reward companies that seriously deal with climate change.
Secondly, we must clarify the investment risks related to green finance.
Cities contributed to 70% or more of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few developing world cities can get credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean buses, energy-efficient buildings and other projects that reduce emissions was affected.
The government and listed banks must intensify their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including taking the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by EIB and co-led with Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Thirdly, we need to modernize the power grid.
Refunds and tax incentives such as those for wind and solar power have promoted their expansion, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar plans to speed up the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies to solve the intermittency issue.
In addition, better grid connectivity can enable regions with excess wind and solar power to supply power to regions with shortages.
The government can take the lead in these two areas and encourage more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has expanded to $136 billion.
However, compared to the $100 trillion global bond market, it is just a drop in the ocean.
Therefore, the EIB is helping to develop sustainable financial standards classification for the EU, so that investors can compare similar projects, just like standard bonds.
More information about the carbon footprint of investments can enable investors to make informed decisions, and thus drive more private investment towards low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
